06185nam a22008895i 9780814763391DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011028196  a97808147633917 a10.18574/nyu/9780814796078.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547978  a(OCoLC)774293614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE540.C47bC45 2012 4aE540.C47bC45 2016 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.708322300aChildren and Youth during the Civil War Era /ced. by James Marten. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChildren and Youth in America ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tPART I . Children and the Sectional Conflict -- t1 “Waked Up to Feel” -- t2 “Train Up a Child in the Way He Should Go” -- t3 “What Is a Person Worth at Such a Time” -- tPART II . Children of War -- t4 A “Rebel to [His] Govt. and to His Parents” -- t5 Thrills for Children -- t6 “Good Children Die Happy” -- t7 Children of the March -- t8 Love in Battle -- tPart III . Aftermaths -- t9 Caught in the Crossfire -- t10 “Free Ourselves, but Deprived of Our Children” -- t11 Reconstructing Social Obligation -- t12 Orphans and Indians -- tPART IV. Epilogue -- t13 Preparing the Next Generation for Massive Resistance -- tDocuments -- tQuestions for Consideration -- tSuggested Readings -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Civil War is a much plumbed area of scholarship, so much so that at times it seems there is no further work to be done in the field. However, the experience of children and youth during that tumultuous time remains a relatively unexplored facet of the conflict. Children and Youth during the Civil War Era seeks a deeper investigation into the historical record by and giving voice and context to their struggles and victories during this critical period in American history.Prominent historians and rising scholars explore issues important to both the Civil War era and to the history of children and youth, including the experience of orphans, drummer boys, and young soldiers on the front lines, and even the impact of the war on the games children played in this collection. Each essay places the history of children and youth in the context of the sectional conflict, while in turn shedding new light on the sectional conflict by viewing it through the lens of children and youth. A much needed, multi-faceted historical account, Children and Youth during the Civil War Era touches on some of the most important historiographical issues with which historians of children and youth and of the Civil War home front have grappled over the last few years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChildren and warzConfederate States of America. 0aChildren and warzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aCurran, Thomas F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeisberg, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Catherine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKickler, Troy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuebler-Wolf, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowery, J. Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarten, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarten, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMintz, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc